The shy albatross is [[endemism|endemic]] breeder to [[Australia]] and it breeds on three island colonies off Tasmania, in the southern Indian Ocean:<ref>{{cite thesis|url=https://eprints.utas.edu.au/14711/1/front-Alderman-thesis.pdf| title=The Shy Albatross (Thalassarche Cauta): Population Trends, Environmental and Anthropogenic Drivers, and the Future for Management and Conservation|first=Rachael Louise |last=Alderman|date=May 2012|type=PhD|publisher=[[University of Tasmania]]| access-date=28 June 2020}}</ref> [[Albatross Island (Tasmania)|Albatross Island]], [[Pedra Branca (Tasmania)|Pedra Branca]], and the [[Mewstone]].<ref>{{cite book
  |last = Brothers  |first = Nigel  |title = Tasmania's Offshore Islands: seabirds and other natural features  |publisher = Tasmanian Museum and Art Gallery  |year = 2001  |isbn = 0-7246-4816-X}}</ref><ref name="Hedd">Hedd, A., et al. (2001a)</ref><ref name="Garnett">Garnett, S. T. & Crowley, G. M. (2000)</ref><ref name="BLI3">BirdLife International (2004)</ref><ref name="Baker">Baker, G. B., et al. (2007)</ref> It is the only albatross endemic to Australia.<ref name=abcendangered/>

Juvenile birds are known to fly as far as [[South Africa]];<ref name="BLI3" /><ref name="Baker" /> otherwise, non-breeding birds can be found throughout the southern oceans, but specifics are hard to determine due to their similarity to the other species.<ref name="ACAP" /><ref name="Double2">Double, M. C., et al. (2003)</ref> It is sometimes found off the [[Pacific]] coast of the United States.

==Conservation==
The [[IUCN]] classifies this species as [[near threatened]],<ref name="iucn status 12 November 2021" /> with an occurrence range of {{convert|23900000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}. The population from an estimate in 2007 was 25,500 breeding birds with 5,100 pairs on [[Albatross Island (Tasmania)|Albatross Island]], 270 pairs on [[Pedra Branca (Tasmania)|Pedra Branca]], and 7,380 on the [[Mewstone]].<ref name="BLI" /> Historically, they were exploited for their feathers, and by 1909 there were only 300 pairs left on Albatross Island.<ref name="Brooke" /><ref name="Johnstone">Johnstone, G. W., et al. (1975)</ref>

Today, [[longline fishing]] still impacts this species but their numbers have been maintained despite this threat.<ref name="Baker" /> They also had an [[avian pox]] outbreak on Albatross Island that has impacted their numbers slightly.<ref name ="Woods">Woods, R. & Gales, R. (2008)</ref> Finally, the [[Australasian gannet]], ''Morus serrator'' is the primary threat to their survival.<ref name="ACAP" />

In June 2020, the [[Australian Government]] changed the status of the bird under the ''[[Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999]]'' from "Vulnerable" to "Endangered", with the bird facing the main threats from [[climate change]] and [[fishery|fisheries]] (as [[bycatch]] victims, either caught in [[trawling]] nets, or on hooks in the longline fishing industry), as well as disease and competition with other seabirds. The change in status is not considered to be due to poor management.<ref name=abcendangered>{{cite web | title='Endangered' status for shy albatross, recognising threats from climate change and fishing | website=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|first=y Georgie |last=Burgess | date=27 June 2020 | url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-06-28/shy-albatross-gains-endangered-species-listing/12395140 | access-date=28 June 2020}}</ref> Listings under state and territory legislation were mostly still "vulnerable" at this time.<ref name=sprat/>

The bird can only be monitored on Albatross Island, as the other two islands are inaccessible, but there are thought to be 15,000 pairs of shy albatross left.<ref name=abcendangered/>

